01:53.803 --> 01:56.426
All of us, when we travel,
look at the places we go,

01:56.461 --> 02:00.499
the things we see
through different eyes.

02:00.534 --> 02:04.331
And how we see them is shaped
by our previous lives.

02:04.365 --> 02:06.126
The books we've read.

02:06.160 --> 02:07.955
The films we've seen.

02:07.989 --> 02:10.991
The baggage we carry.

02:11.026 --> 02:12.960
Years ago, when I first watched

02:12.994 --> 02:16.308
the stunningly beautiful films
of director Wong Kar-wai,

02:16.343 --> 02:19.794
it shaped forever
the way I'd see Hong Kong.

02:19.829 --> 02:21.658
From that point on, my hopes,

02:21.693 --> 02:23.798
my expectations of this city

02:23.833 --> 02:25.731
would be seen through that lens,

02:25.766 --> 02:28.286
a lens that was,
in nearly every case,

02:28.320 --> 02:31.047
pointed by, focused by this man:

02:33.083 --> 02:34.464
Christopher Doyle,

02:34.499 --> 02:36.156
long-time resident of Hong Kong,

02:36.190 --> 02:38.986
known by his Mandarin name
Du Kefeng.

02:39.020 --> 02:40.401
And it won't go away.

02:40.436 --> 02:42.196
His earlier works
with Wong Kar-wai

02:42.231 --> 02:43.473
were distinguished

02:43.508 --> 02:45.372
by unspeakably gorgeous images

02:45.406 --> 02:47.201
of beautiful people
moving through spaces

02:47.236 --> 02:50.204
both unfamiliar
and yet painfully intimate.

02:50.239 --> 02:51.688
Alternately jagged,

02:51.723 --> 02:53.828
frenzied, innovative,

02:53.863 --> 02:55.416
languid, composed,

02:55.451 --> 02:56.762
chaotic.

02:56.797 --> 03:00.214
I obsessed over his work,
fetishized it,

03:00.249 --> 03:02.320
longed to see Hong Kong
like the characters

03:02.354 --> 03:04.908
in so many of his films
longed for each other.

03:04.943 --> 03:07.359
And I feared,
like those characters,

03:07.394 --> 03:09.223
I would be denied.

03:09.258 --> 03:11.225
I was wrong.

03:11.260 --> 03:13.020
The good thing
about the escalator,

03:13.054 --> 03:15.436
it's the best place
to watch people.

03:18.715 --> 03:21.339
♪

03:21.373 --> 03:22.685
The mid-level escalators.

03:22.719 --> 03:24.928
7 million people in Hong Kong,

03:24.963 --> 03:27.034
many of them flowing
through this mile-long

03:27.068 --> 03:28.449
escalator system.

03:28.484 --> 03:31.038
It's Chris Doyle's happy place.

03:31.072 --> 03:33.385
What do you look at
in Hong Kong?

03:33.420 --> 03:35.249
And you've lived here how long?

03:35.284 --> 03:37.596
- Oh, 20, 30 years, almost.
- So...

03:37.631 --> 03:40.358
I-I mean, I've spent more time

03:40.392 --> 03:43.602
in this space
than I have spent in bars.

03:43.637 --> 03:45.570
♪

03:45.604 --> 03:48.538
Look at this, we have people
coming and going.

03:48.573 --> 03:50.091
We have the city passing us by.

03:50.126 --> 03:53.060
We have... to me,
the energy is the noise,

03:53.094 --> 03:54.406
is the people.

03:54.441 --> 03:56.374
I mean, the films that we made

03:56.408 --> 04:00.378
are only this way
because we made them here.

04:00.412 --> 04:03.312
I've made 12 films
within 2 square kilometers

04:03.346 --> 04:05.072
of where we are right now.

04:05.106 --> 04:08.006
In fact, we're gonna pass
by my apartment,

04:08.040 --> 04:09.628
which is
the most famous apartment

04:09.663 --> 04:11.251
in Hong Kong.
You shot in there, right?

04:11.285 --> 04:12.493
It doesn't exist anymore

04:12.528 --> 04:14.323
because the energy changes.

04:14.357 --> 04:17.567
♪

04:17.601 --> 04:19.569
But to tune into the energy...

04:19.603 --> 04:22.158
Ah-ha, hello...
Then we have a movie.

04:22.192 --> 04:23.677
Then we have this conversation.

04:23.711 --> 04:25.920
Then we have something
that the cameraman

04:25.955 --> 04:28.647
is gonna fall over backwards
trying to film.

04:28.682 --> 04:31.305
I think you're just
preparing all the time.

04:31.340 --> 04:33.342
For example,
you watch some of my movies.

04:33.376 --> 04:35.309
- Yes.
- Or we read a book.

04:35.344 --> 04:36.621
- Yeah.
- Or we go out

04:36.655 --> 04:38.208
drinking with friends.
Yeah.

04:38.243 --> 04:39.762
And then bang, bang,

04:39.796 --> 04:43.144
we're doing something
which all of those energies

04:43.179 --> 04:46.803
focus in a way that somehow
connects with other people.

04:46.838 --> 04:49.979
Hello.
What do you want in life?

04:52.395 --> 04:53.845
I mean, you do understand

04:53.879 --> 04:55.295
the impulse, right?

04:55.329 --> 04:57.435
People see work
that you've long ago

04:57.469 --> 04:58.815
just like moved on from.

04:58.850 --> 05:00.955
And they get, you know...
They get a hard-on,

05:00.990 --> 05:02.302
and it won't go away.

05:02.336 --> 05:03.544
I mean, come on, it's...

05:03.579 --> 05:06.202
But the great pleasure is,

05:06.236 --> 05:08.722
I did it...

05:08.756 --> 05:10.448
and it's done.

05:10.482 --> 05:13.623
You want me to reshoot
"Chunking Express"?

05:16.833 --> 05:20.458
♪

05:20.492 --> 05:22.045
But of course
they all do, don't they?

05:22.080 --> 05:23.702
But I don't know how I did it!

05:29.018 --> 05:30.537
Is there a value in

05:30.571 --> 05:32.642
just beautiful people
and objects

05:32.677 --> 05:34.403
moving through space
in beautiful ways?

05:34.437 --> 05:36.266
Is there a value to the color

05:36.301 --> 05:37.992
of a pomegranate?
Yeah, yeah, there is.

05:38.027 --> 05:39.580
Exactly!

05:39.615 --> 05:43.343
This is our challenge,
is to celebrate that.

05:43.377 --> 05:44.827
So-called "beauty" is not,

05:44.861 --> 05:46.415
you know,
"My make-up is so good,

05:46.449 --> 05:49.072
and then I...
I lifted my face a bit."

05:49.107 --> 05:51.074
No.
Beauty is the darkness

05:51.109 --> 05:53.422
and the pleasure
of embracing that

05:53.456 --> 05:55.493
and that giving you
something more

05:55.527 --> 05:58.668
of your experience of life.

05:58.703 --> 06:01.050
I read a script, and it says,

06:01.084 --> 06:02.362
"He looked so sophisticate"...

06:02.396 --> 06:05.572
How do you film "sophisticated"?

06:05.606 --> 06:09.438
How do you convey
the taste of a chili?

06:09.472 --> 06:12.372
We'll never know, but...

06:12.406 --> 06:14.028
the privilege we've been given

06:14.063 --> 06:17.860
is, number one, we've
experienced it personally.

06:17.894 --> 06:21.104
So it becomes part
of who you are.

06:24.142 --> 06:24.642
♪

06:28.629 --> 06:30.217
Leaf Dessert Noodle Shop

06:30.251 --> 06:32.702
is a hundred-year-old
holdout in Central.

06:32.737 --> 06:34.532
Chris has been coming here
for years,

06:34.566 --> 06:37.120
both to film and for this:

06:37.155 --> 06:38.881
Choy noodle soup for him,

06:38.915 --> 06:42.263
and beef brisket noodles
with wonton for me.

06:42.298 --> 06:43.989
♪

06:44.024 --> 06:45.957
Ah, here we go.

06:45.991 --> 06:48.787
So this is family food.

06:51.307 --> 06:52.757
Yeah.

06:54.586 --> 06:56.795
You don't know.
I don't know.

07:04.941 --> 07:07.323
This is the most famous
noodle stand

07:07.357 --> 07:09.325
in cinema history, in Hong Kong.

07:09.359 --> 07:10.740
Has he been
in the films himself?

07:10.775 --> 07:12.915
Many, many, many times.

07:12.949 --> 07:16.781
This is our next nomination
for Hong Kong Film Awards.

07:18.127 --> 07:19.335
Ah, man.

07:19.369 --> 07:21.682
It's good too.

07:24.996 --> 07:25.496
♪

07:37.974 --> 07:39.700
I don't watch movies.
I don't...

07:39.735 --> 07:41.875
watch other people's work.

07:41.909 --> 07:43.601
I can't draw,

07:43.635 --> 07:46.362
but I know if you put this...

07:46.396 --> 07:48.295
♪

07:48.329 --> 07:52.299
And you move it around a bit...

07:52.333 --> 07:54.163
it may take you somewhere.

07:54.197 --> 07:59.237
So, to me, collage is like
the unexpected put together

07:59.271 --> 08:04.311
to perhaps suggest something
that you never thought of.

08:04.345 --> 08:04.845
♪

08:09.661 --> 08:13.527
Our experience actually
gives us a distance

08:13.562 --> 08:16.392
and gives us
this wonderful freedom,

08:16.426 --> 08:19.499
which is called time.

08:19.533 --> 08:21.328
I thought time was running out,

08:21.362 --> 08:22.363
but it's not.

08:22.398 --> 08:24.434
Time is actually

08:24.469 --> 08:27.403
being more condensed,
because we're more focused.

08:27.437 --> 08:27.937
♪

08:35.203 --> 08:38.552
Now our job as artists
is to show you the world

08:38.587 --> 08:40.658
that you think you knew

08:40.692 --> 08:42.866
and celebrate it.

08:42.900 --> 08:46.422
In my wonderful experience
and wonderful journey

08:46.456 --> 08:48.838
with a person
called Wong Kar-wai,

08:48.873 --> 08:51.876
it finally...
After all the films we made,

08:51.910 --> 08:54.568
we made a film called
"In the Mood for Love."

08:57.606 --> 09:00.678
♪

09:00.712 --> 09:04.371
I think everything we did
before then

09:04.405 --> 09:06.235
was preparation.

09:06.269 --> 09:09.134
I think that's it.
If you find this

09:09.169 --> 09:10.584
in your life,

09:10.619 --> 09:14.070
you actually say one sentence

09:14.105 --> 09:16.038
or you make one dish

09:16.072 --> 09:18.247
or you make one image

09:18.281 --> 09:20.318
that is true.

09:20.352 --> 09:21.906
That's pretty good,

09:21.940 --> 09:25.047
because not many people
get that.

09:25.081 --> 09:25.581
♪

09:38.198 --> 09:38.698
♪

09:47.448 --> 09:49.450
♪

10:08.573 --> 10:11.611
♪

11:25.788 --> 11:26.288
♪

11:34.210 --> 11:34.710
♪

11:38.767 --> 11:41.183
The love of money
and shiny new things

11:41.217 --> 11:44.945
is slowly but surely
erasing the past.

11:44.980 --> 11:47.741
So before it's gone,
this is a reminder

11:47.776 --> 11:49.605
of how Hong Kong used to eat,

11:49.639 --> 11:52.228
at dai pai dongs like this one

11:52.263 --> 11:54.196
in Sham Shui Po.

11:54.230 --> 11:58.027
Cheap, delicious food
served from open-air stalls.

11:58.062 --> 12:00.858
Pull up a plastic stool,
crack a beer,

12:00.892 --> 12:02.756
fire up the wok.

12:02.791 --> 12:05.310
So tell me,
what is a dai pai dong?

12:05.345 --> 12:07.485
- "Dai" is "big."
- Big.

12:07.519 --> 12:08.797
"Pai" is "license."

12:08.831 --> 12:10.315
And "dong" is "place."

12:10.350 --> 12:12.870
- So it's...
- So it's "big license place."

12:12.904 --> 12:14.872
Right, and how many of these
are left in, uh...

12:14.906 --> 12:16.736
- 28.
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.

12:16.770 --> 12:18.876
Only 28?
Only 28.

12:18.910 --> 12:20.740
Why? Why don't...

12:20.774 --> 12:22.776
Because the government
doesn't...

12:22.811 --> 12:25.675
They want, uh, street clean.

12:25.710 --> 12:26.884
That's...

12:26.918 --> 12:28.299
That ain't right.
Yeah.

12:28.333 --> 12:30.232
The name of the place
is Keung Kee,

12:30.266 --> 12:33.822
and Gaza Cheung
recently took over as chef.

12:33.856 --> 12:36.134
How do you get
one of the last licenses

12:36.169 --> 12:37.826
for a dai pai dong?
Accident.

12:37.860 --> 12:39.137
- Accident?
- Yeah.

12:39.172 --> 12:41.346
This license is hold
by somebody else,

12:41.381 --> 12:43.314
not by me, but this place,

12:43.348 --> 12:45.419
it's been around for 40 years.

12:45.454 --> 12:47.076
Now, did you change the menu?

12:47.111 --> 12:48.768
Same menu?
No, I changed the menu...

12:48.802 --> 12:50.908
- Right.
- And start a typical,

12:50.942 --> 12:52.910
old-fashioned Chinese meal.

12:54.463 --> 12:55.844
Drunken chicken.

12:55.878 --> 12:57.915
Hacked-up birds
cooked in hot pot,

12:57.949 --> 12:59.295
with medicinal roots and herbs

12:59.330 --> 13:01.021
that will no doubt
make me strong.

13:01.056 --> 13:03.092
What will I feel after I eat it?

13:03.127 --> 13:05.198
- Hyper. I can use...
- Hyper?

13:05.232 --> 13:06.371
- Hyper.
- Energy?

13:06.406 --> 13:07.614
Strength?
Yeah, energy!

13:07.648 --> 13:09.340
Vitality?
No penis in there?

13:09.374 --> 13:10.790
No! No.

13:10.824 --> 13:12.653
- No penis in there.
- I wouldn't eat that.

13:12.688 --> 13:14.034
Myself.
Really?

13:14.069 --> 13:15.725
- Unless you want.
- I've had a fair amount

13:15.760 --> 13:17.555
of penis on this show.
Oh.

13:17.589 --> 13:19.695
♪

13:19.729 --> 13:21.455
A clay-pot dish of fish tripes,

13:21.490 --> 13:22.836
cooked in an egg custard,

13:22.871 --> 13:25.977
topped with
a crispy fried yóu zhá.

13:26.012 --> 13:27.392
Wait a minute, is that egg?

13:27.427 --> 13:28.808
Egg.

13:28.842 --> 13:30.499
So it's like a...
Like a quiche.

13:30.533 --> 13:32.846
Try it.

13:32.881 --> 13:34.365
It's pretty damn good.

13:34.399 --> 13:36.746
Crispy, custardy.

13:36.781 --> 13:38.541
I've never had
anything like this

13:38.576 --> 13:39.888
anywhere in China.

13:39.922 --> 13:42.131
Movies?
Oh, yes.

13:42.166 --> 13:45.548
You know Wong Kar-wai?
I do.

13:45.583 --> 13:48.897
- Do you like him?
- Uh, I love Wong Kar-wai.

13:48.931 --> 13:50.864
Which is your favorite
Wong Kar-wai film?

13:50.899 --> 13:52.728
Oh, "In the Mood of Love."

13:52.762 --> 13:54.212
Me too.

13:54.247 --> 13:55.765
It's the most beautiful film
ever made.

13:55.800 --> 13:57.215
There you are.

13:57.250 --> 13:58.147
No way.

14:01.530 --> 14:02.030
♪

14:11.540 --> 14:12.040
♪

14:30.904 --> 14:31.404
♪

14:36.668 --> 14:40.362
Hong Kong is a mixed culture
with East and West.

14:40.396 --> 14:44.021
- Right.
- Because of the 160 years

14:44.055 --> 14:45.712
as a British colony,

14:45.746 --> 14:49.060
Hong Kong really developed
its own, unique culture.

14:49.095 --> 14:51.373
The people in Hong Kong
really want to see that.

14:51.407 --> 14:53.099
Or for the foreign
people like you,

14:53.133 --> 14:55.653
you want to see, "Oh, it's
really old Hong Kong."

14:58.690 --> 14:59.190
♪

15:04.800 --> 15:07.251
All this is disappearing.

15:07.285 --> 15:09.391
♪

15:09.425 --> 15:12.912
All this could be gone.

15:12.946 --> 15:16.225
It's vanishing before our eyes.

15:16.260 --> 15:18.469
♪

15:18.503 --> 15:20.989
Simon Go is a photographer
who's documented

15:21.023 --> 15:23.992
to 200 small, family-run shops
in the city,

15:24.026 --> 15:26.960
many of them already shuttered.

15:26.995 --> 15:28.858
I go everywhere in Hong Kong.

15:28.893 --> 15:30.930
And I really want to...

15:30.964 --> 15:32.862
To preserve the memories.

15:32.897 --> 15:34.416
Especially in these few years,

15:34.450 --> 15:36.763
I found so many
old shops disappeared

15:36.797 --> 15:39.766
because of some
urban development.

15:39.800 --> 15:41.837
And I think I've got

15:41.871 --> 15:43.804
a mission to preserve that.

15:43.839 --> 15:44.339
♪

15:52.917 --> 15:55.023
To feel sentimental
about the past

15:55.057 --> 15:56.541
is unusual for Hong Kong.

15:56.576 --> 15:58.681
Hong Kong has always been
about changing.

15:58.716 --> 16:00.787
- Yes.
- It's always embraced change.

16:00.821 --> 16:03.686
Realistically,
can these businesses

16:03.721 --> 16:04.894
be protected?

16:04.929 --> 16:06.551
Ah...

16:06.586 --> 16:08.001
It's really difficult to say.

16:08.036 --> 16:10.210
But I think that
when the government

16:10.245 --> 16:12.661
and the Hong Kong people
see more about

16:12.695 --> 16:14.214
our own unique culture,

16:14.249 --> 16:18.115
for many people, try their best
to fight for that.

16:20.669 --> 16:22.395
China Café in Mong Kok,

16:22.429 --> 16:24.638
what's called a cha chaan teng,

16:24.673 --> 16:25.985
or "tea restaurant,"

16:26.019 --> 16:27.503
serving a particularly bizarro

16:27.538 --> 16:30.506
but much-loved bit
of Hong Kong history.

16:30.541 --> 16:32.715
Simon's been coming here
for over 40 years

16:32.750 --> 16:35.477
and orders his favorite:
fried pork cutlet

16:35.511 --> 16:37.479
over rice, with tomato sauce.

16:37.513 --> 16:38.687
Oh!

16:38.721 --> 16:41.345
Thank you.
Wow.

16:41.379 --> 16:43.071
This rice is very popular
in Hong Kong.

16:43.105 --> 16:45.038
- Very popular.
- Especially for a schoolboy,

16:45.073 --> 16:48.041
I came... every time I came
to a cha chaa teng,

16:48.076 --> 16:50.526
I ordered this.
I think it's a...

16:50.561 --> 16:52.321
It's a perfect match for me.

16:54.082 --> 16:57.050
And, well, I had to try this:

16:57.085 --> 16:59.018
macaroni, Spam,

16:59.052 --> 17:01.882
and egg... soup.

17:01.917 --> 17:04.851
I have no idea
where this came from.

17:04.885 --> 17:06.051
I mean, is it a soup?
Is it a stew?

17:06.059 --> 17:07.336
What do I...
Should I break it up?

17:07.371 --> 17:08.717
No, it's okay.

17:08.751 --> 17:10.298
Because in cha chaa teng,
nobody care about...

17:10.305 --> 17:11.582
- Table rules.
- Table manner

17:11.616 --> 17:13.686
or anything, you know?

17:13.722 --> 17:16.173
♪

17:16.207 --> 17:18.520
You know, food and smell

17:18.554 --> 17:22.351
always bring forth
so many memories.

17:22.386 --> 17:25.388
I still remember my parents
and my grandparents,

17:25.423 --> 17:28.357
they would make
some dumpling at home.

17:28.392 --> 17:31.740
And they really worked hard
for prepare the meal

17:31.774 --> 17:34.225
for the family.

17:34.260 --> 17:37.884
The taste is really great
and really sweet.

17:37.918 --> 17:39.265
And...

17:39.299 --> 17:42.130
after my grandmother
and my mother passed away,

17:42.164 --> 17:45.271
I have not any chance
to eat that again.

17:45.305 --> 17:47.997
But about four
or five years ago,

17:48.032 --> 17:49.999
my Auntie made them for me.

17:50.034 --> 17:52.761
When I put it to my mouth,

17:52.795 --> 17:56.075
I burst into tears.

17:56.109 --> 17:58.767
My wife behind...

17:58.801 --> 18:00.596
comforts me.

18:00.631 --> 18:02.150
Speechless.

18:02.184 --> 18:05.222
The taste, the food
recalls so many...

18:05.256 --> 18:08.949
So many memories for me.

18:20.168 --> 18:22.515
♪

18:22.549 --> 18:25.518
In the beginning,
Hong Kong was this:

18:25.552 --> 18:29.522
a fishing village,
like this one.

18:29.556 --> 18:30.056
♪

18:34.147 --> 18:35.528
There you go.

18:35.562 --> 18:37.116
You're gonna give me a camera?

18:37.150 --> 18:39.014
Hell, yeah.

18:39.048 --> 18:42.155
All right, guys, well...

18:42.190 --> 18:44.882
All right,
proceed to smoke weed.

18:47.056 --> 18:48.679
- Can I roll?
- Yeah!

18:48.713 --> 18:50.025
How do I roll?

18:50.059 --> 18:51.682
That button, here.
Yeah, there.

18:51.716 --> 18:54.167
Oh, that's so complicated,
I have to press the button.

18:54.202 --> 18:56.480
♪

18:56.514 --> 18:59.345
Can I close down the aperture
a little bit?

18:59.379 --> 19:01.001
Where is the aperture?
Can you tell me?

19:01.036 --> 19:02.313
You're on a 2-8.

19:02.348 --> 19:05.489
Yeah, you're on it.

19:05.523 --> 19:07.007
I don't smile a lot
on this show,

19:07.042 --> 19:09.907
by the way, but I'm smiling now.

19:09.941 --> 19:10.441
♪

19:19.019 --> 19:20.676
I want to shoot you guys.

19:20.711 --> 19:23.162
So tell us,
you behind the camera,

19:23.196 --> 19:25.198
what are you seeing?

19:25.233 --> 19:27.166
I'm trying really hard
to get footage now.

19:27.200 --> 19:29.168
Really?
Why is that?

19:29.202 --> 19:30.479
This is one of

19:30.514 --> 19:32.171
the most beautiful shots
I've ever made.

19:32.205 --> 19:34.863
I've never made a shot
about cameras before.

19:34.897 --> 19:37.210
So tell us,
what is a camera to you?

19:37.245 --> 19:39.833
I think it's a good thing
to hide behind.

19:42.353 --> 19:43.699
I think, Anthony,

19:43.734 --> 19:46.081
we have one of
the most beautiful images

19:46.115 --> 19:48.221
in all of your film.

19:48.256 --> 19:49.498
This is why we're on...

19:49.533 --> 19:51.535
It's why we're on the damn boat.

19:52.950 --> 19:54.400
Do we have a movie?

19:54.434 --> 19:56.712
- We have a movie.
- We have a movie.

19:56.747 --> 19:58.024
Are you sure we...

19:58.058 --> 19:59.853
I'm worried we didn't record it!

19:59.888 --> 20:01.200
We'll find out in a second.

20:01.234 --> 20:02.856
Then we have to do it in person.

20:02.891 --> 20:04.755
Oh, sit.

20:04.789 --> 20:07.033
Ha!

20:07.067 --> 20:08.690
♪

20:08.724 --> 20:10.795
Tai O is one of
the last fishing villages

20:10.830 --> 20:12.797
in Hong Kong,
on the western side

20:12.832 --> 20:14.351
of Lantau Island.

20:14.385 --> 20:16.249
The families here
have made their living

20:16.284 --> 20:18.251
from the sea for generations.

20:18.286 --> 20:21.530
For Chris Doyle
and his codirector Jenny Suen,

20:21.565 --> 20:23.567
it's a return to the location

20:23.601 --> 20:25.431
of their recent film,
"The White Girl."

20:25.465 --> 20:27.709
So where are we?
I recognize it.

20:27.743 --> 20:29.814
We're in the Venice
of Hong Kong, obviously.

20:29.849 --> 20:31.575
I mean, there we are.
We've got the canals.

20:31.609 --> 20:33.266
We got canals going
in all directions here.

20:33.301 --> 20:34.716
We got
the most beautiful bridges

20:34.750 --> 20:36.062
outside of Venice.

20:36.096 --> 20:37.236
Don't forget, "Hong Kong"

20:37.270 --> 20:39.548
means "fragrant harbor."
Mmhmm.

20:39.583 --> 20:41.447
So it's a good place
to eat, I guess.

20:41.481 --> 20:43.069
Well, you have experience here.

20:43.103 --> 20:44.588
You guys shot a film here.

20:47.591 --> 20:49.386
'Cause you shot like right here.

20:49.420 --> 20:50.939
We literally shot right here.

20:50.973 --> 20:52.561
This is it.
This is the main location

20:52.596 --> 20:54.183
of the film.
This is the main-actually,

20:54.218 --> 20:55.668
when we were prepping the film,

20:55.702 --> 20:57.842
we had looked at
all the fishing villages

20:57.877 --> 20:59.292
around Hong Kong.

20:59.327 --> 21:01.743
And this one
was the most complete,

21:01.777 --> 21:04.608
in the sense that
it's a real community,

21:04.642 --> 21:06.092
as opposed to, you know,

21:06.126 --> 21:07.507
something closer to the city.

21:07.542 --> 21:09.164
And it's a metaphor
for Hong Kong,

21:09.198 --> 21:11.477
because we feel Hong Kong
is disappearing also.

21:11.511 --> 21:13.617
And so much of what we're doing

21:13.651 --> 21:17.759
is to keep something
that makes us unique alive.

21:20.796 --> 21:23.420
♪

21:23.454 --> 21:26.768
For lunch, there's corn
and fish maw soup...

21:26.802 --> 21:28.425
♪

21:28.459 --> 21:30.944
Fried fish maw
with dried scallop,

21:30.979 --> 21:32.877
dried shrimp, and pork.

21:32.912 --> 21:34.327
♪

21:34.362 --> 21:36.467
Salted egg yolks
are left in the sun

21:36.502 --> 21:37.986
to cure slightly,

21:38.020 --> 21:40.471
then served over rice.

21:40.506 --> 21:43.336
Crispy pork belly
cooked in shrimp paste

21:43.371 --> 21:44.717
and yu choy.

21:44.751 --> 21:46.857
♪

21:46.891 --> 21:49.446
I drink to heaven!

21:49.480 --> 21:52.034
Under which we stand together
and enjoy this.

21:52.069 --> 21:53.864
We drink to earth because...

21:53.898 --> 21:56.487
Well, there's no more earth,
but we drink to sea today.

21:56.522 --> 21:58.489
I drink to heaven,
I drink to earth,

21:58.524 --> 21:59.801
and I drink to you.

21:59.835 --> 22:01.250
Isn't that
the most beautiful way

22:01.285 --> 22:02.631
to share a drink with friends?

22:04.046 --> 22:06.359
I have a tricky moral
question, though, for you.

22:06.394 --> 22:07.464
A moral question? Me?

22:07.498 --> 22:08.672
- Yes. Yeah.
- Oh, great.

22:08.706 --> 22:10.467
I was...
I'm a recovering Catholic.

22:10.501 --> 22:12.365
I can answer any moral question.

22:12.400 --> 22:14.471
We are changing the world
by looking at it

22:14.505 --> 22:16.887
through cameras, as...
As happens every time

22:16.921 --> 22:19.717
you look at real people,
the real world,

22:19.752 --> 22:20.891
real places.

22:20.925 --> 22:23.583
Where does that fall
in your comfort zone?

22:23.618 --> 22:25.095
When the character
of the place changes.

22:25.102 --> 22:26.379
Ah, yeah, it's true.

22:26.414 --> 22:28.588
We're part of the problem,
not... right?

22:28.623 --> 22:31.384
The only way is just
not to be cynical about it.

22:31.419 --> 22:33.869
We want the audience
to feel a certain way.

22:33.904 --> 22:36.596
But if the process is open,
then I think it has integrity.

22:36.631 --> 22:38.667
If we've done what we love
in integrity,

22:38.702 --> 22:41.256
if we've tried to be
as true as possible

22:41.290 --> 22:43.258
to how we see things,

22:43.292 --> 22:45.260
perhaps, perhaps...
Mmhmm.

22:45.294 --> 22:47.124
It transfers.

22:50.403 --> 22:53.441
♪

22:53.475 --> 22:55.512
The only function of what we do

22:55.546 --> 22:57.376
with art or with anything

22:57.410 --> 22:59.447
is to give voice
to the unspoken,

22:59.481 --> 23:02.415
to give it a form
that it's never been

23:02.450 --> 23:03.899
perceived in before.

23:03.934 --> 23:05.694
We can't change
the evolution of history

23:05.729 --> 23:07.593
or the gentrification...
You can't stop that.

23:07.627 --> 23:10.458
But at least you can say,
"Look what you're losing."

23:10.492 --> 23:12.218
That's all... that's the only...

23:12.252 --> 23:14.703
All we can do is give
an image to an idea.

23:17.948 --> 23:18.448
♪

23:44.699 --> 23:46.942
The infamous Chunking Mansions

23:46.977 --> 23:48.737
sit right smack in the center

23:48.772 --> 23:50.843
of high-end Tsim Sha Tsui,

23:50.877 --> 23:53.570
right around the corner
from swank hotels

23:53.604 --> 23:56.262
and surrounded by shops
selling luxury goods

23:56.296 --> 23:59.438
and designer brands.

23:59.472 --> 24:02.026
5 housing blocks and 17 stories

24:02.061 --> 24:05.271
containing, well,
everything and everybody

24:05.305 --> 24:07.929
who the rest of Hong Kong
would like to ignore.

24:11.173 --> 24:14.763
While many locals avoid it
for its, well, reputation

24:14.798 --> 24:16.593
and for some
of its less legitimate

24:16.627 --> 24:18.457
business enterprises,
shall we say,

24:18.491 --> 24:21.114
it offers cheap rooms and asylum

24:21.149 --> 24:23.600
for people,
specifically refugees,

24:23.634 --> 24:25.498
from all over the world

24:25.533 --> 24:28.225
and even a taste of home.

24:28.259 --> 24:31.953
When I met Selena
about 15 years ago,

24:31.987 --> 24:35.128
we decided to open
a restaurant in Hong Kong.

24:35.163 --> 24:38.477
But most
of the African guys here,

24:38.511 --> 24:40.409
to be honest,
they don't have money.

24:40.444 --> 24:42.308
Most of them, they are refugees.

24:42.342 --> 24:46.036
So how do we sell
the food to them?

24:49.764 --> 24:51.869
So we opened us a kitchen

24:51.904 --> 24:55.563
for all of them to come
and cook their food,

24:55.597 --> 24:57.841
enjoy and meet new friends.

24:57.875 --> 25:00.360
Then, uh,
they can enjoy themself.

25:00.395 --> 25:02.535
That's how we started.

25:07.540 --> 25:09.508
I moved from Hong Kong
to Canada.

25:09.542 --> 25:11.544
My husband moved from Ghana

25:11.579 --> 25:13.097
to China and Hong Kong.

25:13.132 --> 25:14.547
But we know that if you move

25:14.582 --> 25:16.894
to another country,
it's not easy.

25:16.929 --> 25:20.001
So we try to provide
a place for them

25:20.035 --> 25:22.279
to feel like they are at home.

25:22.313 --> 25:23.936
After we have this place,

25:23.970 --> 25:26.007
we see a lot of happy face.

25:26.041 --> 25:28.112
I see a lot of them
gains weight.

25:28.147 --> 25:29.873
They have a big tummy.

25:29.907 --> 25:31.599
And I say, "Okay, that's..."

25:31.633 --> 25:33.428
"what we are doing
is the right thing."

25:33.462 --> 25:33.962
♪

25:42.989 --> 25:44.404
Tell me about this building.

25:44.439 --> 25:45.751
It's legendary, of course.

25:45.785 --> 25:47.546
For me, I think it's...

25:47.580 --> 25:48.892
It's really a very unique place.

25:48.926 --> 25:50.928
Like it's a place
that when I come out

25:50.963 --> 25:52.689
from my home,
it's a place that I know

25:52.723 --> 25:54.207
I'm gonna pass in some way.

25:54.242 --> 25:56.071
It's a place I meet new friends.

25:56.106 --> 25:58.695
It's a place that gives me
a lot of confidence.

25:58.729 --> 26:01.318
When I'm in here,
I know where to go.

26:01.352 --> 26:05.080
I know who to talk to.
I know which food to eat.

26:07.635 --> 26:09.119
In the '60s and '70s,

26:09.153 --> 26:11.639
the city relied
on cheap refugee labor.

26:11.673 --> 26:13.226
No longer.

26:13.261 --> 26:15.815
Today, most refugees
are seeking asylum

26:15.850 --> 26:18.059
anywhere they can find it.

26:18.093 --> 26:20.509
Many here are stuck in limbo.

26:20.544 --> 26:22.926
Can't go back, can't work,

26:22.960 --> 26:24.444
can't leave.

26:24.479 --> 26:26.654
Jahan fled Iran six years ago

26:26.688 --> 26:28.310
just ahead of the secret police.

26:28.345 --> 26:30.968
Shermarke is a student
from Somalia,

26:31.003 --> 26:32.625
who had
equally compelling reasons

26:32.660 --> 26:35.179
to leave his home.

26:35.214 --> 26:36.767
What brought you here?

26:36.802 --> 26:38.769
The basic reason
for me to come here

26:38.804 --> 26:40.633
was finding a safe haven, right?

26:40.668 --> 26:41.772
- Yes.
- I mean,

26:41.807 --> 26:43.256
you're in a safe place.

26:43.291 --> 26:44.837
That's the only thing
you're thinking about

26:44.844 --> 26:46.045
in that moment.
You came from Iran.

26:46.052 --> 26:47.606
- Yeah.
- Why did you come

26:47.640 --> 26:49.435
to Hong Kong?
Why did I leave Iran?

26:49.469 --> 26:51.368
The short version goes,

26:51.402 --> 26:52.783
they wanted to kill me,
and I said,

26:52.818 --> 26:54.751
"No thank you."
I end up here.

26:54.785 --> 26:56.373
It was... It wasn't something

26:56.407 --> 26:58.133
that I would dream of
or I planned.

26:58.168 --> 27:00.515
I have no idea
about the currency,

27:00.549 --> 27:01.758
the government.

27:01.792 --> 27:03.449
No, nothing at all.

27:07.211 --> 27:09.110
♪

27:09.144 --> 27:10.698
How long have you been here now?

27:10.732 --> 27:12.285
Uh, going to be six years.

27:12.320 --> 27:13.632
- Six years?
- Yeah.

27:13.666 --> 27:14.805
They tell me that

27:14.840 --> 27:17.808
even if you be accepted
as a refugee,

27:17.843 --> 27:19.638
you are not welcome to stay.

27:19.672 --> 27:21.778
You have to be resettled
in another country.

27:21.812 --> 27:23.469
- Right.
- They are telling me

27:23.503 --> 27:25.298
while you're staying,
you are not allowed

27:25.333 --> 27:28.647
to work, study, even volunteer,

27:28.681 --> 27:32.029
or contribute in society
in any way.

27:32.064 --> 27:33.548
But you can exist.

27:33.582 --> 27:34.963
That's it.
You can exist, yeah.

27:34.998 --> 27:37.483
- You believe me or not...
- Hold on one sec.

27:37.517 --> 27:38.829
Let me reset.

27:38.864 --> 27:40.900
- How is it going?
- Good.

27:40.935 --> 27:42.488
You believe everything he says?

27:42.522 --> 27:44.214
- Yes.
- Oh, Jesus!

27:46.181 --> 27:47.693
I think we're good.
We got a lot of bread.

27:47.700 --> 27:49.039
But if they can bring that
up for eating...

27:49.046 --> 27:50.496
Actually, they brought it in.

27:50.530 --> 27:51.808
Let's just leave it there.

27:51.842 --> 27:54.189
Can we push you
a little bit to your right?

27:56.571 --> 27:57.606
All right?
Let me know

27:57.641 --> 27:58.884
when everybody's up.

27:58.918 --> 28:00.506
Roll sound.

28:03.543 --> 28:05.822
♪

28:05.856 --> 28:07.858
So what is your hope?

28:07.893 --> 28:09.273
What are your prospects

28:09.308 --> 28:10.999
of being able to go to America?

28:11.034 --> 28:12.829
I would love to go to America.

28:12.863 --> 28:15.452
But it's not the way
U.S. sees me

28:15.486 --> 28:16.833
qualified to be there.

28:16.867 --> 28:20.353
Right before
Donald Trump was appointed

28:20.388 --> 28:22.252
to be the American president,

28:22.286 --> 28:24.288
I had my last interview.

28:24.323 --> 28:27.429
And then, unfortunately,
you know what he did?

28:27.464 --> 28:29.362
He banned six, seven countries,

28:29.397 --> 28:30.743
including my country.

28:30.778 --> 28:32.262
So now, currently, I'm...

28:32.296 --> 28:34.782
I'm studying
and I'm planning to move

28:34.816 --> 28:36.266
to somewhere else.

28:36.300 --> 28:38.958
♪

28:38.993 --> 28:40.857
To be honest, um...

28:40.891 --> 28:43.376
I'm not a big fan of hope.

28:43.411 --> 28:45.309
I have no hope in the system.

28:45.344 --> 28:46.725
Or I have no hope

28:46.759 --> 28:49.210
in someone gonna
get me out of here.

28:49.244 --> 28:50.729
I'm trying by my own.

28:50.763 --> 28:54.077
I'm trying to be
my best as possible here

28:54.111 --> 28:57.425
and seek by myself
for ways to get out

28:57.459 --> 29:00.428
of Hong Kong and the system.

29:00.462 --> 29:00.962
♪

29:15.788 --> 29:16.288
♪

29:30.147 --> 29:33.185
♪ You've said you've tried

29:33.219 --> 29:35.946
♪ He just can't comprehend

29:35.981 --> 29:38.707
♪ What is that thing

29:38.742 --> 29:41.710
♪ That we're trying
to defend ♪

29:41.745 --> 29:44.679
♪ No one can decide

29:44.713 --> 29:47.268
♪ How this is going to end

29:47.302 --> 29:47.802
♪

29:51.720 --> 29:53.101
♪ It's in my hot blood

29:53.136 --> 29:54.620
♪ I can't, I can't

29:54.654 --> 29:55.794
♪ I can't,
I can't ♪

29:55.828 --> 29:57.554
♪ I can't, I can't

29:57.588 --> 29:58.658
♪ I can't do it anymore

29:58.693 --> 30:00.384
♪ I can't, I can't

30:00.419 --> 30:01.938
♪ I can't,
I can't ♪

30:01.972 --> 30:03.456
♪ I can't, I can't

30:03.491 --> 30:05.148
♪ I can't,
I can't ♪

30:05.182 --> 30:07.460
♪

30:08.876 --> 30:10.705
Have you eaten
anything this morning?

30:10.739 --> 30:12.672
Uh, no.
I'm hungry, man.

30:12.707 --> 30:14.398
Oh, come to me.
There we go.

30:14.433 --> 30:17.125
"David Boring"
is a five-piece band

30:17.160 --> 30:19.714
fronted by Janice Lau
and Jason Cheung,

30:19.748 --> 30:22.579
their backgrounds
in architecture and medicine

30:22.613 --> 30:24.961
seemingly at odds
with their somewhat more

30:24.995 --> 30:26.825
nihilistic music.

30:26.859 --> 30:28.198
You know this place.
You've eaten here before

30:28.205 --> 30:30.000
many times, 'cause you guys

30:30.035 --> 30:32.244
went to school
right in the neighborhood.

30:32.278 --> 30:33.762
It's very popular with students.

30:33.797 --> 30:35.419
We always come after deadlines,

30:35.454 --> 30:37.490
so first thing in the morning,

30:37.525 --> 30:39.251
4:00 a.m., all students.

30:39.285 --> 30:40.873
- Yeah.
- And the place is

30:40.908 --> 30:42.668
even more crowded
than right now, yeah.

30:42.702 --> 30:45.153
What are the things
that you see disappearing

30:45.188 --> 30:48.743
in Hong Kong that are
most alarming to you?

30:48.777 --> 30:51.228
Certainly a degree of freedom.

30:51.263 --> 30:54.231
As someone who's
born and raised here,

30:54.266 --> 30:55.992
you can definitely feel a change

30:56.026 --> 30:57.717
in the last five to ten years.

30:57.752 --> 31:00.617
And what we are trying to do
with our music

31:00.651 --> 31:02.895
is to address
that sort of change.

31:02.930 --> 31:04.932
Are you able
to say what you want?

31:04.966 --> 31:06.174
- Yeah.
- Yes.

31:06.209 --> 31:07.693
- Yeah.
- In ten years?

31:07.727 --> 31:09.384
I don't know.
Right now, yes.

31:09.419 --> 31:10.799
Say what you want.

31:10.834 --> 31:12.070
You are actually allowed
to play music.

31:12.077 --> 31:13.699
You're allowed to do
whatever you want.

31:13.733 --> 31:15.114
But there's no venue.

31:15.149 --> 31:16.944
There's no space
for you to practice.

31:16.978 --> 31:20.016
I think this is how
the society is limiting

31:20.050 --> 31:22.225
the possibility of young people,

31:22.259 --> 31:24.365
in that sense.

31:24.399 --> 31:27.057
Whatever your feelings
about how things are going,

31:27.092 --> 31:28.887
some things are a constant,

31:28.921 --> 31:31.717
a comfort, a birthright.

31:31.751 --> 31:33.546
Like egg custard buns.

31:33.581 --> 31:35.583
Egg yolks,
sweetened condensed milk.

31:35.617 --> 31:37.826
When steamed,
the custard returns

31:37.861 --> 31:39.621
to more molten form.

31:39.656 --> 31:40.933
Braised chicken feet.

31:40.968 --> 31:42.555
First fried, then braised

31:42.590 --> 31:44.143
with ginger and star anise

31:44.178 --> 31:47.250
before being finished
in the steamer.

31:47.284 --> 31:48.803
Is it possible to make a living

31:48.837 --> 31:50.460
playing your kind of music?

31:50.494 --> 31:51.737
- No.
- Impossible.

31:51.771 --> 31:53.049
- No.
